<h3>Sub</h3>
<p>A <strong>&#1588;&#1583;&#1577;</strong>, <em>shadda,</em> is a diacritical mark used to mark a double letter. With the Roman alphabet we show double letters by writing the two single ones next to one another (as in &ldquo;accompany, &ldquo;little&rdquo; or &ldquo;letter&rdquo;), but Arabic is more efficient. You don&rsquo;t use the <em>shadda</em> (or<em> tashdid</em>) all the time, but in cases of potential confusion or simply to be meticulous, it&rsquo;s common enough. <em>Shadda</em> could be written <strong>&#1588;&#1583;&#1617;&#1577;</strong>. (The <em>shadda</em> looks like a miniature <strong>&#1587;</strong>; I&rsquo;m sure there&rsquo;s a reason.) A <strong>&#1588;&#1591;&#1617;</strong>, <em>sha&#7789;&#7789;</em> , is a shore, a coast. <em>Sha&#7789;&#7789; al-&lsquo;arab</em> is where the Tigris and Euphrates rivers converge. The verbal stem, <em>sha&#7789;&#7789;a</em> (spelled like the noun &mdash; (<strong>&#1588;&#1591;&#1617;</strong>), is &ldquo;to go to extremes, exceed proper bounds, to digress.&rdquo; The verb <strong>&#1588;&#1617;&#1585;&#1617;</strong> <em>sharra</em>, is &ldquo;to be bad, evil.&rdquo;<em> Sharr</em> (<strong>&#1588;&#1617;&#1585;&#1617;</strong>) is the noun for evil or mischief, injustice, harm or damage.&nbsp;</p>
<p>A friend tells me that the letter Sh&icirc;n is the letter of the suspect or questionable. <em>Shu&rsquo;m</em> is bad luck, a bad omen. (A <em>mutash&acirc;&rsquo;im</em> is a pessimist.) <em>Shirk</em> is idolatry or polytheism, usually used negatively. <em>Sham&acirc;t </em>is Schadenfreude. Shay&#7789;&acirc;n is the devil (or a devil, one among others). <em>Shay&#7789;&acirc;n</em> could possibly be derived from an Arabic stem, but it seems pretty clearly a loan word. (I&rsquo;ve run into a number of possible sources, but whatever it is, it is probably the same origin that gives us &ldquo;Satan&rdquo; -- Greek &Sigma;&alpha;&tau;&acirc;&nu;).&nbsp;</p>
<p>There is a four-consonant verbal stem, SH-R-M-&#7788;, which gives you <strong>&#1588;&#1585;&#1605;&#1591;</strong>, <em>sharma&#7789;a</em>, to tear to shreds. It is related to the noun <em>sharm&ucirc;&#7789;a</em> (<strong>&#1588;&#1585;&#1605;&#1608;&#1591;&#1577;</strong>), a shred or a tatter, but you are much more likely to hear it as the word for a prostitute. Like many four-consonant stems, it seems to be based on a loan word, in this case <em>sharm</em> in Middle Persian, &ldquo;shame.&rdquo;</p>
<p>At some point in their history, books in the category &ldquo;unclassifiable&rdquo; become a genre. &ldquo;Unclassifiable&rdquo; is a category, but probably not the same as a genre. With a lot of unusual books, it can take a while before we know where to put them. Perhaps Ahmad Faris Ash-Shidy&acirc;q&rsquo;s always surprising <em>Al-S&acirc;q &lsquo;al&acirc; al-s&acirc;q</em>,<em> Leg</em> <em>over leg</em> (1955), is still waiting for a place to live. It has a plot, the growth and education of a young man named Al-F&acirc;riy&acirc;q (a variant of the author&rsquo;s name), but the biographical episodes are not what you remember most. It&rsquo;s the digressions. A sentence may be interrupted with a list pages long. One chapter begins &ldquo;If anyone read the end of the previous chapter and then his servant came and called him to dinner, causing him to leave the book and rise...&rdquo; (there follows a two-page list of things that might have happened to interrupt, some of them mysterious little stories in themselves, and concludes), &ldquo;...he will certainly have forgotten all the physical and moral incidents which have befallen the F&acirc;riy&acirc;q...&rdquo; (trans. the late Humphrey Davies, pp. 55-56). Then again, there is a chapter five lines long (entitled <em>F&icirc; l&acirc; shay&rsquo;</em>, &ldquo;On Nothing&rdquo;). <em>Leg over leg</em> has predecessors. Readers have suggested the unclassified Rabelais, which makes sense (though lately Rabelais has been assigned a genre, &ldquo;carnivalesque&rdquo;) and Lawrence Sterne (novel, sort of). A Spanish friend suggests <em>Don Quixote</em> (proto-novel?). One or all of them could be influences. Shidy&acirc;q&rsquo;s <em>shuhra,</em> his reputation, hasn&rsquo;t suffered. Literary histories list him regularly, and don&rsquo;t quite know how to judge him. If there is a dilemma, there is, as Kamran Rastegar has suggested (in the first authoritative study of <em>Leg over leg</em>), a targeting issue: &ldquo;Intentionally obscure, Shidy&acirc;q&rsquo;s work by no means anticipates a single readership, which may be why some scholars have somewhat plaintively seen him to have &lsquo;<em>almost</em> achieved greatness&rsquo;&rdquo; (<em>Literary Modernity between the Middle East and Europe</em>, 112).</p>
<p>The name <strong>&#1588;&#1583;&#1740;&#1575;&#1602;</strong>, Shidy&acirc;q is not as strange and unclassifiable as <em>Al-S&acirc;q &lsquo;ala al-s&acirc;q</em>, but it is not a common name, and it doesn&rsquo;t really sound Arabic. After you ask around from friends who know these things, you find that <em>shidy&acirc;q</em> is a loan word, meaning a role in the Orthodox church. Shidy&acirc;q was a Christian most of his life (he converted to Islam in 1860): a <em>shidy&acirc;q </em>is a sub-deacon, a loan word from Syriac. Syriac borrows the word from Greek &delta;&iota;&aacute;&kappa;&omicron;&nu;&omicron;&sigmaf;, <em>di&aacute;konos</em> (a deacon), which looks a little like the English word &ldquo;deacon&rdquo; (also German <em>diacon</em>, French <em>diaconat</em> or Italian <em>di&aacute;cono</em>). Then there is the prefix SH, which must mean something like &ldquo;sub-,&rdquo; but it remains an SH which is, for me at least, an unknown.</p>
<h3>X</h3>
<p>Sh&icirc;n is for <strong>&#1588;&#1610;&#1569;</strong> , <em>shay&rsquo;</em>, the word for &ldquo;thing&rdquo; in Arabic. It can be used to form a negative, as in Cairo dialect, where one produces a &ldquo;not&rdquo; by putting a negative particle (<em>ma</em>, ูุง) in front of a word and -<em>sh</em> at the end. That sh sound is short for <em>shay&rsquo;</em>, as we might say &ldquo;not a thing&rdquo; or in French &ldquo;<em>ne... pas</em>&rdquo; (&ldquo;not a step&rdquo;). Thus <strong>&#1605;&#1593;&#1604;&#1588;</strong>, <em>ma&lsquo;lish</em>, &ldquo;it doesn&rsquo;t matter&rdquo; (literally <strong>&#1605;&#1575; &#1593;&#1604;&#1610;&#1607; &#1588;&#1740;&#1569;</strong> &ldquo;there is nothing on it&rdquo; or perhaps &ldquo;nothing to it&rdquo;) or <strong>&#1605;&#1601;&#1610;&#1588;</strong>, <em>maf&icirc;sh,</em> &ldquo;there isn&rsquo;t any&rdquo; (literally <strong>&#1605;&#1575; &#1601;&#1610;&#1607; &#1588;&#1740;&#1569;</strong> , &ldquo;there is nothing in it,&rdquo; &ldquo;nothing there,&rdquo; or a whole series of other negations. (It is one of the two words G&eacute;rard de Nerval learns in his <em>Voyage en Orient</em>, translating &ldquo;pas du tout.&rdquo; His source is the woman he has taken on as a slave in Cairo.)</p>
<p>Among the many uses of <strong>&#1588;&#1610;&#1569;</strong>, like &ldquo;thing&rdquo; in any language, is to refer to the undefined: &ldquo;some thing,&rdquo; &ldquo;any thing.&rdquo; It was used that way in Al-Khwarizm&icirc;&rsquo;s mathematics. Twenty-eight plus <em>shay&rsquo;</em> equals thirty-two. &ldquo;Twenty-eight plus <em>some thing</em> equals thirty-two.&rdquo; We would write it as 28 + x = 32, with the letter X instead of <em>shay&rsquo;</em>.</p>
<p>The story goes that &ldquo;x&rdquo; as the translation of <em>shay&rsquo;</em> is the result of a linguistic mismatch. The mismatch is, the story goes, that the Sh&icirc;n sound does not exist in Spanish (or in Latin, or for that matter in Greek), and consequently when translators at the Toledo School of Translation, founded by Alfonso in the 13th century, translated Muhammad ibn Musa Al-Khwarizmi into either Castilian or Latin, the <strong>&#1588;</strong> sound presumably baffled them. The story continues that they had to borrow a letter which represented a sound close to it, CH (as in &ldquo;chill&rdquo; or &ldquo;chore&rdquo;), and chose the letter X because the Greek letter Chi was (supposedly) pronounced that way. In another version X was pronounced that way (SH) in Spanish. (X can be the SH sound in some dialects, I am told, as with the city Xela in Guatemala.) Terry Moore (the science journalist, not the graphic novelist) recounts the story in an article on the subject in <a href="https://cosmosmagazine.com/mathematics/why-x-marks-unknown-0"><em>Cosmos</em> magazine</a>. He concludes &ldquo;X is the unknown because you can&rsquo;t say <em>sh</em> in Spanish.&rdquo;&nbsp;</p>
<p>I would very much like that explanation to make sense, since it is, after all, a proof by linguistics, but the theory doesn&rsquo;t explain why a translator would want to convey the pronunciation of <em>shay&rsquo;</em> at all, rather than just translating it. A word meaning &ldquo;thing,&rdquo; after all, exists both in Spanish (<em>cosa</em>) and in Latin (<em>res</em>). What could be easier? A translator is not obliged to transliterate. Meanwhile, the Greek letter X (Chi) is definitely not pronounced like our SH. (It&rsquo;s pronounced like Arabic <strong>&#1582;</strong>, KH. That&rsquo;s why the KH sound in Arabic is sometimes represented in English transliteration by an X.) The first Latin translation of Al-Khwarezmi that I know of, <em>Liber algebrae et almucabola</em>, was by Robert of Chester (12th century), presumably a speaker of English. SH would not have been a mystery to him. Middle English had a perfectly usable SH sound. He wouldn&rsquo;t have needed Greek Chi even if he wanted to transliterate.&nbsp;</p>
<p>That <em>shay&rsquo;</em> became X there is no doubt. The letter X used to represent the unknown, our equivalent of Al-Khwarezmi&rsquo;s <strong>&#1588;&#1610;&#1569;</strong>, is said to be a 17th-century development initiated in Descartes&rsquo; book on geometry. (<a href="https://gizmodo.com/why-do-we-use-the-letter-x-to-represent-the-unknown-1588933259">Gizmodo.com</a> seems a trustworthy source on this.)&nbsp;</p>
<p><a href="https://legacy-www.math.harvard.edu/~knill/teaching/summer2019/exhibits/algebra/AlgebraMohammedBenMusa.pdf"><em>The Algebra of Mohammed Ben Musa</em></a>, an 1831 translation by Frederic Rosen, has no trouble simply translating<em> shay&rsquo;</em> into English as &ldquo;thing&rdquo;: thus, in his translation, the equation we would describe as (10 &ndash; x) (10 + x) takes on a perfectly comprehensible form, even in English: &ldquo;If the instance be, &lsquo;ten minus thing&rsquo; to be multiplied by &lsquo;ten and thing,&rsquo; then you say &lsquo;ten times ten is a hundred, etc....&rsquo;&rdquo; (25).</p>
