<h3>Sweet</h3>
<p>The stem SH-K-R means &ldquo;to thank.&rdquo; <em>Shukran</em> in Arabic, the most frequently heard term for &ldquo;thank you,&rdquo; is its simplest noun form: <em>shukr</em>, thankfulness, plus an accusative ending, a kind of adverbial &ldquo;thankfully,&rdquo; &ldquo;with thanks.&rdquo; As the word emigrates it could be a lesson in what happens when a term in Arabic becomes a loan word. In Urdu it gets a new suffix, <em>shukria</em>. In Persian the commonest thank-you is an adjective form from the same stem, <em>mutashakker,</em> with the Persian verb &ldquo;to be&rdquo; added, <em>mutashakker-am</em>, &ldquo;I am thankful.&rdquo; In Turkish the form is <em>te&#351;ekk&ucirc;r ederim</em>, &ldquo;I thank you.&rdquo;&nbsp;</p>
<p class="illo"><img src="../_img/shin4.png" width="300" align="right" style="margin-right:-80px" /></p>
<p>In Persian <em>shekar </em>is sugar (no connection to <em>shukr</em>). When it became a loan word in Arabic, the SH became an S. Arabic has the linguistic apparatus to retain the SH, but in this case it didn&rsquo;t. And so, Persian <em>shekar </em>became in Arabic <em>sukkar</em>. It was absorbed into a pre-existent stem, S-K-R, to be drunk, confused, disoriented, and led a double life. <em>Sukrat al-mawt</em> in the Qur&rsquo;&acirc;n is the confusion or stupor of death (Q 50.19). There is in classical Greek a word &sigma;&iacute;&kappa;&epsilon;&rho;&alpha;, <em>s&iacute;kera</em>, a sweet alcoholic drink. It has been suggested that it is a loan word from a Semitic stem. It seems reasonable. If Arabic <em>sukkar </em>and<em> sikera </em>are in fact cognates, it leads us to imagine the occasion, tavern, conflict or mixed party where Greek speakers and fellow drinkers who spoke Arabic might have had a conversation in which the word came up and the Greek speakers liked the sound. </p>
<p><em>Sh&icirc;r</em> in Persian is milk, also proverbial for sweetness. (I shouldn&rsquo;t simplify the story. <em>Sh&icirc;r</em> also means &ldquo;lion&rdquo; and&ldquo;water tap.&rdquo; Why not?) <em>Shir</em> takes an adjective form (and name), <em>shirin</em>, &ldquo;sweet.&rdquo; Another Sh&icirc;n word represents more intense sweetness. In the last chapter of <em>Candide</em>, Candide and his companion Martin famously get the idea to focus on cultivating their garden. They are living in Istanbul: the idea comes from a Turkish farmer who invites them in to eat with his family. The first items on the menu are &ldquo;plusieurs sortes de sorbets qu'ils faisaient eux-m&ecirc;mes,&rdquo; &ldquo;all sorts of <em>sorbets</em> which they made themselves.&rdquo; The immediate ancestor of <em>sorbet </em>is Turkish, <em>&#351;erbet</em> (earlier still, Persian,<em> sharbat</em><strong>).</strong> An earlier predecessor is the Arabic verb <em>shariba</em>, to drink. <em>Shar&acirc;b</em> is a general word for a beverage. (In Persan it means &ldquo;wine.&rdquo; English &ldquo;syrup&rdquo; comes from the same stem. &ldquo;Syrup&rdquo; in the sense we use the word would be something like the Persian Sh&icirc;n word <em>sh&icirc;reh</em> (from <em>sh&icirc;r</em>).&nbsp;</p>
<p><em>Sharibtu</em>: I drank. <em>Sharibn&acirc;</em>: We drank. A particularly famous line from the great thirteenth-century mystical poet &lsquo;Umar Ibn al-F&acirc;ri&#7693; shows how the word can be laundered, so that drinking and getting drunk are ironic ways to describe the mystical exercises of<em> dhikr</em> and the experience of ecstasy:</p>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>&#1588;&#1585;&#1576;&#1606;&#1575; &#1593;&#1604;&#1740; &#1584;&#1705;&#1585; &#1575;&#1604;&#1581;&#1576;&#1740;&#1576; &#1605;&#1583;&#1575;&#1605;&#1577;<br />
</strong><strong>&#1587;&#1705;&#1585;&#1606;&#1575; &#1576;&#1607;&#1575; &#1605;&#1606; &#1602;&#1576;&#1604; &#1571;&#1606; &#1740;&#1582;&#1604;&#1602; &#1575;&#1604;&#1705;&#1585;&#1605;</strong></p>
<p><em>Sharibn&acirc; &lsquo;al&acirc; dhikri al-hab&icirc;bi mud&acirc;ma<br /></em><em>Sukirn&acirc; bi-h&acirc; min qabli an yukhlaq al-kirm</em></p>
<p>[In memory (<em>dhikr</em>) of the beloved / we drank (<em>sharibn&acirc;</em>) a wine; / we were drunk with it before creation of the vine &ndash; tr. Emil Homerin, 54]</p>
</blockquote>
<p>The crescent moon, Ibn al-F&acirc;ri&#7693; continues, was a cup for that drink, a crescent that fills up with light from the <em>shams</em>, the sun, like a soul imbibing illumination.</p>
<h3>Sunrise</h3>
<p>In the pantheon of supernatural figures who govern the plot of <em>Gilgamesh</em> there is a deity named Shamash, a god connected somehow with the sun. Gilgamesh and Enkidu pray to him when they go out to fight Humbaba. It&rsquo;s easy to see a recognizable Semitic stem in Shamesh if we think of <em>shams</em> in Arabic, Sh&icirc;n word for the sun. In adjective form, <em>shams&icirc;</em>, it describes a solar calendar, as distinct from a <em>qamar&icirc;</em> or lunar calendar.&nbsp;</p>
<p class="illo"><img src="../_img/shin5.png" width="300" align="right" style="margin-right:-80px" /></p>
<p>The relations of sun and moon are everywhere. You&rsquo;ll find them in the first lesson of a course in Arabic, where you learn that there are two categories of letters, fourteen each, categories named for the moon and sun, differentiated by the way they react when they are placed directly after the letter L&acirc;m of the definite article, -<em>al</em>. The Moon letters, <em>al-&#7717;ur&ucirc;f al-qamariyya</em> (Alif, Ba&rsquo;, Jim, &#7716;a&rsquo;, Kh&acirc;&rsquo;, &lsquo;Ayn, Ghayn, F&acirc;&rsquo;, Q&acirc;f, K&acirc;f, M&icirc;m, Waw, Yay and Ha [hawwaz]) leave the L alone, as in the words <em>al-&#7717;ur&ucirc;f, </em>&ldquo;the letters,&rdquo; and<em> al-qamariyya </em>&ldquo;the lunar ones,&rdquo; where the L remains intact. The Sun Letters, <em>al-&#7717;ur&ucirc;f al-shamsiyya</em> (Ta, Tha, D&acirc;l, Dh&acirc;l, Ra, Z&#846;a, S&icirc;n, Sh&icirc;n, &#7778;ad, &#7692;al, &#7788;a, Za, L&acirc;m and N&ucirc;n), make the L&acirc;m of <em>al</em>- disappear, or rather, assimilate. Thus the term written <em>al-&#7717;ur&ucirc;f al-Shamsiyya</em> in official transcription is pronounced differently, <em>al-&#7717;ur&ucirc;f ash-shamsiyya</em>. Shamm al-Nas&icirc;m is pronounced <em>Shamm an-nas&icirc;m</em>. <em>Al-ra&#7717;m&acirc;n al-ra&#7717;&icirc;m</em> is <em>Ar-ra&#7717;m&acirc;n ar-ra&#7717;&icirc;m</em>. <em>Kawkab ash-Sham&acirc;l </em>is the North Star.</p>
<p><em>Ash-Sham&acirc;l</em> is the north, but it is also the word for &ldquo;the left&rdquo; (as opposed to <em>Al-yam&icirc;n</em>). A map with north on the left would put east at the top (perhaps because that is where sunrise takes place?). Actually, in vintage maps it&rsquo;s the norm, oriented with East at the top and West at the bottom. No doubt there is a cause and effect here &ndash; whether the map affects the use of the word or the other way around. (It has nothing to do with Mecca, by the way. Maps east of the Holy Land are still likely to have East at the top and North on the left.)&nbsp;</p>
<p>&ldquo;East&rdquo; is <strong>&#1588;&#1585;&#1602;</strong>, <em>sharq</em>, whose stem (SH-R-Q) means in its verbal form &ldquo;to rise,&rdquo; as in &ldquo;sunrise.&rdquo; The noun form <strong>&#1605;&#1588;&#1585;&#1602;</strong>, <em>mashriq</em> is the place of sunrise, another word for the East, the land of the rising sun. (The etymological basis is comparable to our word &ldquo;Orient,&rdquo; from Latin <em>orior</em>, to rise. The opposite, &ldquo;Occident,&rdquo; is from Latin <em>occidere</em>, to fall down, to set.) A <em>Sharq&icirc;</em> is a person from the east (an &ldquo;oriental&rdquo;). Our word &ldquo;saracen&rdquo; may come from its plural, <em>sharq&icirc;y&icirc;n</em>. (The OED is doubtful about this.) A <em>mustashriq</em> is someone whose demeanor is characteristic of the east, a synonym for &ldquo;oriental,&rdquo; but, by a grammatical transformation I don&rsquo;t really understand, it also designates the contrary, a student of the Middle East, an orientalist, someone who looks at the Middle East from outside. <em>Al-istishr&acirc;q</em> is the study of the East, orientalism. It is the word used to translate into Arabic Edward Said&rsquo;s term &ldquo;orientalism.&rdquo;&nbsp;</p>
<p>We know the argument, and we rehearse it repeatedly &ndash; that students of the field tend to distance themselves, to speak of their subject with smug superiority. (I&rsquo;ve already rehearsed it once today.) Said&rsquo;s argument is nuanced: he acknowledges that there are experts who resist the pressures towards ethnocentrism, over-simplification and the weakness of projecting our cultural anxieties on non-Europeans. The focus of <em>Orientalism</em>, the book, however, is centered on the expert who gives in to the traditional temptation (of western condescension). It requires a very powerful book to counterbalance a whole tradition. A slowly building, towering argument, however logical, isn&rsquo;tt necessarily enough. <em>Orientalism</em> accomplishes this, however, in briefer form. What drives his argument is a wide, powerful idea, but an idea that narrows to a sharp point. The word &ldquo;orientalism&rdquo; is the sharp point.</p>
<p>We may underestimate the sheer brilliance of that title. Titles can sum up the argument, but this one propels it. &ldquo;Orientalism&rdquo; (the word) before <em>Orientalism</em> (the book) had been a colorless, antiquarian term, like the half-defined thing it described, amorphous and seemingly innocent. But to make it the name of a political phenomenon gives it a rare weight. The word takes on fetish value, its own force of gravity. <em>Orientalism </em>simply makes it impossible for anyone to use the word &ldquo;orientalism&rdquo; again without taking Edward Said&rsquo;s use of it into account.&nbsp;</p>
<p class="illo"><img src="../_img/shin6.png" width="200" align="right" style="margin-right:-80px" /></p>
<p>The ability of a word to travel from one context to another is a sign of its power. There are no guarantees, however, that once broken loose, charged with that rhetorical intensity, the word will retain its nuances. In academic discourse the word &ldquo;orientalism&rdquo; has taken simpler and simpler, less and less nuanced forms. It can be wielded as an insult in ways that would have surprised Edward Said. Come for the concept; stay for the slogan.</p>
<p>The evolution &ldquo;Orientalism&rdquo; has undergone is a process like that of the word <em>jihad.</em> <em>Jih&acirc;d</em> narrowed from a general term used to describe religious striving, a term with both an outward and an inward meaning, until it has come to represent, to the ignorant, nothing more than a terrorist imperative. (The shrunken form of <em>jih&acirc;d</em> is used this way in public discourse, to describe any violence with religious motives.) One might want to reel it back from the simplified meaning, but is probably impossible: once a word has taken on its narrow, more powerful form, we&rsquo;re stuck with it. It will keep its authority. We&rsquo;re not going to defuse it.&nbsp;</p>
<p>Sh&icirc;n word <em>shaykh</em> (anglicized as sheik) is used for more than one level of authority. It&rsquo;s not a word that possesses power, but a word which describes it. Etymologically a <em>shaykh</em> (Turkish <em>&#351;eyh</em>) simply means someone &ldquo;of a certain age&rdquo; (from Arabic SH-Y-KH, to grow old). It can mean an old man. (The three men who arrive at the house of the three ladies of Baghdad in the <em>1001 Nights</em> are<em> shuy&ucirc;kh</em>, <em>shayk</em>s.) It can be the head of a family or a tribe (our word &ldquo;elder&rdquo;). It can mean a ruler of a sheikdom (a <em>mashyakha</em>). It can mean a scholar in theology. It can mean the head of a Sufi order.&nbsp;</p>
<p><em>Sh&acirc;h</em> is a word with less free play. It refers to a king, a sovereign, very much a Persian form of authority, with an etymology rooted in old Indo-European forms. (The name we spell Xerxes is from the same stem.) Perhaps its limited semantic field also makes it a brittle term. When the ruler of Iran was deposed in 1979 the word fell with him. Bandar Shah, once a port on the shore of the Caspian, is now Bandar Turkmen. The extraordinary Masjad-e Sh&acirc;h mosque in Esfahan (Royal Mosque in English) is now the Mashjad-e Em&acirc;m.</p>
