<h3>Tree of Pearls</h3>
<p>Sometimes you don&rsquo;t know what to call a person in power. A <em>shajara </em>is a tree, a <em>shajarat an-nasab</em> is a genealogical tree. Shajarat ad-Durr, a tree of pearls, is a name of importance to the history of royal authority in the Arab world. Fatma Mernissi tells the story of the woman named <em>Shajarat ad-Durr</em> as part of a demonstration that, though most rulers have been men, in practice there have also been Arab women who occupied the throne and taken on the role of queen, but that there is no tradition to validate it, and thus no language to account for it. Mernissi asks, what do you call a queen? The phenomenon of Shajarat ad-Durr&rsquo;s rise to power in 1249 wasn&rsquo;t immediately a problem of naming. Before finding a title for her you have to wonder how she got there, what networks of power made it possible. She was born a slave, taken as a concubine by Sultan A&#7779;-&#7778;alih Najm Ad-Din Ayyub. When he died of sickness during the campaign against Louis ix&rsquo;s crusade (the seventh, 1249-50), she concealed the fact of his death and took power behind the scenes. It&rsquo;s only when she made her control public that it became possible to ask Fatima Mernissi&rsquo;s question.&nbsp;</p>
<p>The power which brings her to the court is first the companionship of the sultan. The second opportunity is the power vacuum created by his death, which wouldn&rsquo;t have been sufficient in itself; she has to demonstrate her intelligence. A&#7779;-&#7778;&acirc;li&#7717;&rsquo;s son could have claimed the right to succeed him, but he was assassinated. (If you read enough accounts you hear claims that she arranged it.) The additional vacuum created by the disappearance of still another male claim to authority would not have been sufficient cause for her rise to power, but her popularity with the army adds to the equation. (I can&rsquo;t say how she became popular with the army: in this story it&rsquo;s a given.) Once she&rsquo;s in power we can consider the need for a title. It couldn&rsquo;t be <em>khal&icirc;fa</em>. There was a weak caliph in Baghdad, Musta&lsquo;&#7779;im, who presumably ruled the entire Islamic world under that title. (He wouldn&rsquo;t rule for long.) Shajarat ad-Durr opted for the generic title <em>malika</em>, the feminine form of <em>malik</em>, king. (One also sees her referred to as <em>sultana,</em> holder of power.) She ruled alone for eighty days and then married &lsquo;Izz ad-D&icirc;n Aybak, the head of the army, in order to stay on as an unacknowledged counselor. (It ended badly.)</p>
<p>There are coins in which her name is found, but they were struck after the eighty days of her reign. Her name is displayed jointly with that of her second husband &lsquo;Izz ad-D&icirc;n. You can see poorly focused photos of the coin <a href="https://www.google.com/search?q=Genzoman+Shajarat+al-Durr&amp;source=lnms&amp;tbm=isch&amp;sa=X&amp;ved=2ahUKEwjQyOOYk6foAhWSLc0KHW7LALQQ_AUoAnoECAYQBA&amp;biw=1217&amp;bih=615#imgrc=Es2b4hwOvQ0pLM">online</a>.</p>
<p>They look clumsily cut, with awkward calligraphy: <em>al-Musta&lsquo;&#7779;imiyah a&#7779;-&#7778;alihiyah Malikat al-Muslim&icirc;n walidat al-Malik al-Man&#7779;&ucirc;r Khal&icirc;l Am&icirc;r al-Mu'min&icirc;n</em>: (The Musta&lsquo;&#7779;imiyyah, the pious Queen of the Muslims, Mother of King Al-Mansur Khalil [she had a son named Khalil],<em> am&icirc;r</em> of the faithful). That first adjective, <em>al-musta&lsquo;&#7779;imiyyah</em>, is the adjective form of the caliph&rsquo;s name, Musta&lsquo;&#7779;im. Using it as her title was, as Mernissi points out, &ldquo;a pathetic admission of her weakness, a desperate attempt to gain his goodwill&rdquo; (90). Though Musta&lsquo;&#7779;im was a weak ruler, in his role as commander of the faithful he still had the power to humiliate her. The greater, more material insult was his ability to shut down her role as<em> malika</em>, &ldquo;queen.&rdquo; (It&rsquo;s with this humiliation that the eighty days ended.) Musta&lsquo;&#7779;im&rsquo;s judgment on her claim to power in Egypt was that &ldquo;he was ready to provide them with some capable men, if no more existed in Egypt, since they were reduced to choosing a woman&rdquo; (Mernissi 29). Mernissi also adds that, seven years later, Musta&lsquo;&#7779;im was killed when Hulagu invaded Baghdad and destroyed his kingdom. (The Mongols, by the way, never succeeded in occupying Egypt.)</p>
<p>Musta&lsquo;&#7779;im revealed the gap in Shajarat ad-Durr&rsquo;s power. Her dilemma of improvising a term (<em>malika</em>) for queen demonstrates the linguistic power vacuum. Still, the absence of explicit definition of her role can be a gap in the wall which hems her in. The unstated, the unclassifiable, can be an advantage. One of the sources of power is a lapse of attention on the part of one&rsquo;s opponent. She certainly won out in the memory of storytellers.</p>
<p>Sultan A&#7827;-Z&#846;&acirc;hir Baybars al-Bunduqdari (d. 1277), came to power in Egypt in 1260, four years after Shajarat ad-Durr&rsquo;s death<strong>, </strong>three years after the fall of Baghdad. The story of his life generated a long epic romance, <em>S&icirc;rat a&#7827;-</em>Z<em>&acirc;hir Baybars</em> (a <em>s&icirc;ra</em> being a story of heroism). Among a multitude of characters in the romance is a character named Shajarat ad-Durr. In this version she is a daughter of the caliph Muqtadir (895-932 -- it&rsquo;s an anachronism). A&#7779;-&#7778;&acirc;li&#7717; Najm ad-D&icirc;n marries her in order to establish his legitimacy as Sultan in Egypt. She protects the hero Baybars; &lsquo;Izz ad-D&icirc;n Aybak appears as the heavy, a claimant to the throne, killed by Shajarat ad-Durr.&nbsp;</p>
<p>Shajarat ad-Durr is also the subject of a historical novel by Jurji Z&#846;aydan (1861-1914). To read it (in an unusually beautiful English translation, by Samah Selim) is to see an additional account of power. It&rsquo;s in the style of Walter Scott or Cooper, a translation of historical events into the mood of romance. In a romance, no matter how accurate the historical background, the sources of power are personal. We learn about her rivalry with the envious concubine Sallafa, who engineers a break between the heroine and her faithful confidante Shwaykar. There are only very good or very bad characters.&nbsp;</p>
<p>The name still hasn&rsquo;t worn out completely. Shajarat ad-Durr shows up in a cute pixar-style image on <a href="https://www.rejectedprincesses.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/shajaraldurr-354x500.jpg">the web page</a> by Jason Porath. She is also one of the characters depicted in a repertoire of drawings by the graphic artist Gonzalo Ord&oacute;nez Arias (pen-name, Genzoman). In his image, she is dressed superhero-style, not warmly, unencumbered, mostly in just a cape and billowing <em>shelv&acirc;r</em> which reaches up a few inches above the knee. She flourishes an oddly shaped <em>shamshir</em>, a scimitar. For some reason the blade has a notch like a bottle opener and rows of metal rings at the lower and upper ends (three each). She stands with one foot on a little strip of rubble. The pyramids are in the background, underneath what seems an incoming sand storm. Her black hair flutters behind her like the cape, as if with a mind of its own. She seems the sort of character who would think in terms of strength rather of strategy.</p>
<h3>Knight&rsquo;s Move</h3>
<p><strong><em>&#1588;&#1593;&#1585;</em></strong>, <em>shi&lsquo;r</em>, is poetry. The same three letters give us <em>sha&lsquo;r</em>, hair. The same stem with still another set of vowels is Shi&lsquo;r&acirc;&rsquo;, the star Sirius, brightest star in the celestial catalog. In a list of the Lord&rsquo;s powers in the sura named The Star (<em>An-najm</em>) &ldquo;He is the lord of Shi&lsquo;r&acirc;&rsquo;&rdquo; (53.49). There may be a link between hair and a star: it is possible to think of brightness as fuzziness, thus the stem Sh-&lsquo;Ayn-R. On the other hand, Arthur Jeffery&rsquo;s<em> Foreign Vocabulary of the Qur&rsquo;&acirc;n </em>psays with certainty that Shi&lsquo;r&acirc;&rsquo; is a loan word from Greek &Sigma;&epsilon;&iacute;&rho;&iota;&omicron;&sigmaf;, <em>se&iacute;rios</em>, &ldquo;hot.&rdquo;&nbsp;</p>
<p>One of the most problematic early caliphs was Mu&lsquo;&acirc;wiyya (602-680), not simply because his name looks so hard to pronounce. (The accent is on the second syllable: Mow-OW-we-ya. In Persian it&rsquo;s Mow-&acirc;vi-YEH.) His rise to power between the assassination of &lsquo;Uthm&acirc;n (656 A.D.) and that of &lsquo;Al&icirc; (661), the period referred to as the first <em>fitna</em> (the first big scandal in the new Muslim community), marks Mu&lsquo;&acirc;wiyya as a brilliant tactician, embodying secular force rather than spiritual authority. He described his philosophy of authority subtly:</p>
<p>I do not employ my sword when my whip suffices me, nor my whip when my tongue suffices me; and were there a single hair (<strong>&#1588;&#1593;&#1585;</strong>, <em>sha&lsquo;r</em>) between me and my subjects, I would not let it be snapped. (Nicholson, <em>A literary history of the Arabs</em>, 194 / Ya'qubi [ed. Houtsma] ii.283, l. 8 seq).</p>
<p>The image of a fragile filament kept intact by a sensitive hand which can loosen its grip or pull tight, in response to a hand on the other side, is an image quite unlike Mu&lsquo;&acirc;wiyya&rsquo;s reputation.&nbsp;</p>
<p>One of the sources of contention between &lsquo;Ali and Mu&lsquo;&acirc;wiya was rule over ash-Sh&acirc;m. (Sh&acirc;m is Syria. Sh&acirc;m&icirc;, is the adjective &ldquo;Syrian,&rdquo; also a term for flat bread, which evidently is thought to be from there.) The most famous Sh&acirc;m&icirc; in English history was Philippe Stamma (d. ca. 1755), who came to England from Aleppo and ended up a regular at Slaughter&rsquo;s Coffee House in St. Martin&rsquo;s Lane (hangout of Hogarth &amp; Thomas Gainsborough). Stamma&rsquo;s notoriety came from his brilliance at chess. His book, <em>Essai sur le jeu des &eacute;checs o&ugrave; l&rsquo;on donne quelques r&egrave;gles pour le bienjouer et remporter l'avantage par des coups fins et subtils, que l'on peut appeler les secrets de ce jeu </em>(1741, translated four years later as <em>The Noble Game of Chess</em>) is famous for having emphasized the importance of the endgame and having devised a notation to show chess moves which is, more or less, the one we still use.</p>
<p>If we wanted to put together an inventory of visitors to Europe from the Arab world, we could include chess itself. It was pretty well known that chess came from the east. (Even the hoax called Maelzel&rsquo;s Automaton Chess Player, which was displayed in Europe and the U.S. from 1770 to 1854, in which an automaton played chess, supposedly in the manner of a computer, but in fact guided by a chess master hidden underneath the apparatus, was presented to audiences by a master of ceremonies in Middle Eastern clothes. It was called The Mechanical Turk.) Wikipedia tells you that Maelzel&rsquo;s spectacle defeated both Napoleon and Benjamin Franklin. Rex Sorgatz, a friend of the Alphabet, pointed out, to my surprise, that Charles Babbage saw the automaton in 1819, shortly before he began work on the Difference Engine (<em>The Encyclopedia of Misinformation</em>, 2018, p. 131).&nbsp;</p>
<p>If you believed it was a machine determining the moves, would you also believe that it was invented east of Europe? If on the other hand you saw through it, would you believe that the invisible chess master was from the Islamic world? You can find lists of the chess masters who were hired to sit in that claustrophobic space, all of whom seem to have been non-claustrophobic Europeans.</p>
<p>During a period when there was an alliance between Charlemagne and the Abbasid empire, the caliph Harun ar-Rashid gave the emperor among other presents (elegant cloth, a water clock, an elephant named Abu &lsquo;Abb&acirc;s) a chess set. So chess, like camels and magic lanterns, became one of those images that represented the middle east as early as the 9th century.&nbsp;</p>
<p>Over time it became familiar and less exotic.&nbsp;</p>
<p>One of Omar Khayyam&rsquo;s quatrains describes us humans as chess pieces and <em>falak</em> (&ldquo;the heavens&rdquo;) as the chess players. (<strong>&#1605;&#1575; &#1604;&#1593;&#1576;&#1578;&#1711;&#1575;&#1606;&#1740;&#1605; &#1608; &#1601;&#1604;&#1705; &#1604;&#1593;&#1576;&#1578; &#1576;&#1575;&#1586;</strong>, <em>M&acirc; lo&lsquo;batg&acirc;nim-o falak lo&lsquo;batb&acirc;z</em>, &ldquo;we&rsquo;re the pieces; the sky is the player,&rdquo; in FitzGerald&rsquo;s paraphrase, &ldquo;But helpless Pieces of the Game He plays/upon this chequer-board of nights and days...&rdquo; FitzGerald 5th edition # 69). And afterwards we get put back, one by one, into the box of non-being (<em>&#7779;and&ucirc;q-e &lsquo;adam</em>). He takes it for granted that we know the game and doesn&rsquo;t even bother to name it. (It&rsquo;s not an uncommon image. The same metaphor occurs in <em>Don Quixote </em>&mdash; Part two, chapter 12 (one of its most beautiful chapters).</p>
<p>Chess is the Sh&icirc;n word <strong>&#1588;&#1591;&#1585;&#1606;&#1580;</strong> <em>sha&#7789;ranj</em>. With five consonants, it&rsquo;s not likely to be an indigenous Arabic word. (William Jones traced it to Sanskrit <em>chaturanga</em>.) As the story goes, the way Ferdowsi tells it in the <em>Sh&acirc;hn&acirc;meh</em>, the king of India sent a chess board and chess pieces as a gift to the Persian king Nushirvan with the challenge to figure out how it&rsquo;s played. They get one hint: &ldquo;the rules are the rules of war.&rdquo; The legendary perfect advisor Bozorjmehr is said to have figured out what the moves must be. The story is doubtful. (It&rsquo;s a lot to expect, of even the best advisors, to determine the rules of chess from the appearance of the board and the shape of the pieces.) Perhaps it would be just as hard to learn military strategy from the rules of chess. There is, however, an example of it.&nbsp;</p>
<p>Philippe Stamma, in <em>The Noble Game of Chess</em>, described a young man in Syria who spent all his time playing chess, for which his father reproached him. The son insisted that chess was useful. The father doubted it and, to straighten him out, sent him on a road trip for business.</p>
<p>When the young man was on his road, the father sent four men after him to rob him. When the son found himself opposed to these robbers, he dismounted quickly, abandoned his horse, and taking refuge behind the walls and hedges, escaped. (<em>Essai sur le jeu des &eacute;checs, </em>157-58, trans. Charles Tomlinson, 75)</p>
<p>Abandoning your horse is a response that could have occurred to anyone, chess player or not, but the son&rsquo;s explanation is an argument for the ability of the imagination to claim its power:</p>
<p>&ldquo;As soon as I was attacked,&rdquo; said he, &ldquo;I bethought myself of an expedient frequently adopted at chess, viz., to sacrifice my horse to save my life and my money: in the same way as at chess I sometimes sacrifice my knight, in order to save my king or my queen...This little story [says Stamma], is far more pleasantly related in the Arabic, in which language the knight [<em>cavalier</em>] is called a horse [<em>cheval</em>].&rdquo; (<em>Essai sur le jeu des &eacute;checs, </em>158-59<em>, </em>trans, Tomlinson, 75)</p>
<p>The names of the pieces retain imagery from the Arab world (and points further east). The knight is <em>faras</em>, the horseman, but we knew that already from the shape of the piece. (We should add that the son in the story sacrificed a horse, not a horse-man.) The rook was a <em>rukh</em> (no idea why), though in contemporary Arabic it is the fortress (<em>&#7789;</em><em>&acirc;biyya</em>). The linguistic dilemma Fatima Mernissi examines, what to call a queen in Arabic, is not an issue in this case. What we call the queen is the <em>waz&icirc;r</em> (Persian <em>farzin</em>), the advisor. The bishop is an elephant (<em>f&icirc;l</em>). The king is a <em>malik</em>, in Persian a <em>sh&acirc;h</em>.</p>

